"Closed source is not closed enough according to Microsoft's latest strategy for its upcoming 64-bit Vista operating system. The software giant is taking security into its own hands by banning security vendors from nosing at its new OS. It is not allowing anyone near the kernel to patch it or otherwise. In retaliation there has been a public backlash from security firm Mc Afee accusing Microsoft of putting the entire Internet at risk. Microsoft has created a Patchguard feature, which stops any third party applications from accessing the kernel. The company has pointed to a long miserable trail of malware, which security vendors have failed to prevent in the past. And hackers have been enable to insert rootkits allowing remote control of Windows programs. It is arguing the less people who get intimate with Vista the better for everyone. It definitely spells the end of old-fashioned full disclosure. But MS may have to open up yet if the EU decide its new hardline lock-down is anticompetitive. Philip Hunter reports."
